Patricia M. -- t9. Country Before Money? Economic Globalization and National Identity in New Zealand / rTrue, Jacqui -- tConclusion: The Meaning and Contemporary Significance of Economic Nationalism / rHelleiner, Eric -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIs economic nationalism an outdated phenomenon in light of globalization? Economic Nationalism in a Globalizing World demonstrates the enduring, and even heightened, economic significance of national identities and nationalism in the current age. The volume's contributors, pioneers in the reinterpretation of economic nationalism, explore diverse ways in which national identities and nationalism continue to shape contemporary economic policies and processes.The authors examine the question in a range of geographical contexts and issues: European Union food politics, competitiveness strategies in New Zealand, East Asian development strategies, Japanese liberalization, monetary politics in Quebec and Germany, and post-Soviet economic reforms. Together, the cases explore the policy breadth of nationalism. It is not just a "protectionist" ideology but is in fact associated with a wide variety of economic policies, including support for economic liberalization and globalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aEconomic policy. 0aGlobalization. 0aNationalism. 0aProtectionism. 4aGeneral Economics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aHelleiner, Eric, eeditor.1 aPickel, Andreas, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750940uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726620423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501726620.jpg  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015